1354":"1354","about 1352":"about 1352","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Great Orton, Cumberland, England":"Great Orton, Cumberland, England","England":"England","Stainton in Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Stainton in Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Orton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Orton in Cambridgeshire, Leicestershire, Northamptonshire, Warwickshire, and Westmorland. All those in England share a second element from Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, but the first element in each case is more difficult to determine. Examples in Cambridgeshire and Warwickshire are on the banks of rivers, so these are probably derived from Old English <i>ōfer</i> ‘riverbank’; in other cases it is impossible to distinguish between <i>ofer</i> ‘ridge’ and <i>ufera</i> ‘upper’. Orton in Westmorland is probably formed with the Old Norse byname <i>Orri</i> ‘black-cock’ (the male black grouse). Orton near Fochabers, Scotland, is of uncertain etymology.","Americanized form of Norwegian <b>Årtun</b>: habitational name from the farm name Årtun, found in six places, e.g. in the province of Rogaland, a compound of the genitive case singular of Old Norse <i>á</i> ‘small river’ and <i>tún</i> ‘farm yard (surrounded by buildings)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Urton","meanings":["English (Derbyshire): variant of   Orton  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Giles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Much altered English vernacular form of the Late Latin name <i>Aegidius</i>, from Greek <i>Aigidios</i> (a derivative of <i>aigidion</i> ‘kid, young goat’), via Old French <i>Gide</i>. It was the name of an 8th‐century saint who, according to tradition, was an Athenian citizen who fled to Provence because he could not cope with the fame and adulation caused by his power to work miracles, in particular by healing the lame and crippled. This was not a particularly common name in the Middle Ages and its use seems to have been confined to certain families and localities."],"variants":[{"name":"Gyles","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Giles ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":27,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Giles Orton of Stainton was born in 1310, in Great Orton, Cumberland, England, his father, John Mautravers, was 31 and his mother, Joan de Orreton, was 23. He married Maud before 1345. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. He died on 3 August 1369, in Stainton in Carlisle, Cumberland, England, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1310–3 August 1369":"1310–3. august 1369","1310–1369":"1310–1369","–Female":"Surnud","1322–Female":"1322–Surnud","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1367–Female":"1367–Surnud","1345–1414":"1345–1414","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","1354–Female"